ch support the health and well-being of the Kiholo community,&rdquo; said lead researcher Dr. Jack Kittinger, director of Conservation International&rsquo;s Hawai&rsquo;i program. &ldquo;These benefits are likely common to coral reef fisheries across the globe, supporting key food security functions, cultural practices as well as local livelihoods.&rdquo;</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 5.0pt 36.0pt;\"><span style=\"color: #212529;\">The results of the study suggest that similar coral reef fisheries around the world provide the people who depend on them with the same types of benefits. The survey found that 58 percent of the caught seafood is kept for home consumption, 34 percent is given away and only 8 percent sold to commercial markets. &ldquo;We found that the vast majority of the catch is kept for home consumption or given away as part of cultural practices, showing the important role that this bay plays in sustaining our community,&rdquo; said Jenny Mitchell, a board member of Hui Aloha Kiholo. &ldquo;When Kiholo thrives, so do we.&rdquo;</span></p>\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 5.0pt 36.0pt;\"><span style=\"color: #212529;\">By surveying fishermen for an entire year, researchers were able to estimate that the fishery produced more than 7,300 pounds of seafood per year for the community of people. Nearly 60 percent of the catch is used for subsistence, contributing to community food security. Geographic analysis of community beneiciaries showed that 20 percent of seafood procured is used for sociocultural events that are important for social cohesion.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right; margin: 0cm 0cm 5.0pt 36.0pt;\" align=\"right\"><span style=\"color: #212529;\">(Diadaptasi dari&nbsp;<em>http://www.conservation.org/NewsRoorn/pressreleases/Pages/Reef&shy;to&shy;Table&shy;Small&shy;Scale&shy;Reef&shy;Fisheries&shy;Provide&shy;Big&shy;Beneits&shy;to&shy;People.aspx</em>)</span></p>\n<p>What can be inferred from the passage?</p>',1157,58,'The benefit